content_dict["Abstract"] = [
    "Abstract—Object detection under adverse weather conditions, particularly fog and haze, remains one of the most critical challenges for the deployment of reliable autonomous vehicles and outdoor surveillance systems. Atmospheric scattering attenuates light and introduces noise, drastically reducing contrast, washing out colors, and blurring edge features. As a result, the performance of standard computer vision models, which are predominantly trained on clear-weather datasets, degrades significantly. This paper presents the 'Foggy Image Enhancer', a comprehensive, full-stack platform designed to algorithmically restore visibility in foggy road scenes and quantitatively evaluate the resultant impact on object detection efficacy. The proposed system integrates a sophisticated multi-algorithmic pipeline encompassing Contrast Limited Adaptive Histogram Equalization (CLAHE), non-linear Gamma Correction, Bilateral Filtering, and a physics-based Dark Channel Prior (DCP) restoration model. We utilize the YOLOv5 deep learning architecture as the benchmark detection engine to perform real-time inference on both the unadulterated and algorithmically enhanced imagery. Our empirical results demonstrate that physics-based restoration via DCP significantly improves the confidence scores and the total count of correctly identified entities (vehicles, pedestrians, traffic signs) in dense fog environments, achieving confidence gains of over 50%. The platform is engineered with a decoupled architecture, utilizing a FastAPI backend for intensive tensor operations and a React-based frontend for intuitive user interaction. Furthermore, the entire system is containerized and deployed across Hugging Face Spaces and Vercel, demonstrating a highly scalable, cloud-native approach to complex computer vision tasks. This paper extensively documents the theoretical underpinnings, system architecture, implementation challenges, and rigorous evaluation methodologies of the Foggy Image Enhancer.",
    "Keywords—Foggy Image Enhancement, Dark Channel Prior, YOLOv5, Autonomous Driving, FastAPI, React, Cloud Deployment, Computer Vision."
]

content_dict["1. Introduction"] = [
    "The advent of autonomous driving and smart city infrastructure has necessitated the development of robust perception systems capable of operating under all environmental conditions. While modern deep learning models have achieved near-human accuracy in object detection tasks during clear weather, their reliability plummets dramatically when exposed to adverse meteorological phenomena such as fog, haze, rain, and snow. Fog, in particular, is an atmospheric condition characterized by a high concentration of suspended water droplets or ice crystals. These particles scatter and absorb light as it travels from the object to the camera sensor, leading to a phenomenon known as atmospheric attenuation. The resulting images suffer from severe contrast degradation, color shifting, and a loss of high-frequency spatial details—the exact features that convolutional neural networks (CNNs) rely upon for feature extraction and object localization.",
    "The primary motivation for this research stems from the critical safety implications of perception failures in autonomous vehicles. A split-second delay or a missed detection of a pedestrian or another vehicle due to fog can lead to catastrophic consequences. Therefore, developing a resilient algorithmic layer that can preprocess and enhance visual data before it reaches the detection model is of paramount importance. Rather than attempting to retrain massive object detection networks on exhaustively large and difficult-to-acquire datasets of varying fog densities, this project explores the paradigm of algorithmic image restoration. By mathematically inverting the effects of light scattering, we aim to recover the underlying scene radiance, thereby providing standard, pre-trained object detectors with imagery that closely resembles their training distributions.",
    "This project introduces the 'Foggy Image Enhancer', an end-to-end software platform designed to bridge the gap between theoretical image processing algorithms and practical, scalable deployment. The system offers a comprehensive suite of enhancement techniques, ranging from traditional histogram operations to advanced physics-based models. By integrating these algorithms with the YOLOv5 object detection framework, the platform provides an immediate, quantifiable measure of enhancement efficacy. Users can upload degraded images, process them through multiple algorithms simultaneously, and visually and numerically compare the results via an intuitive web interface.",
    "The objectives of this research are multifaceted. First, we aim to rigorously implement and optimize four distinct image enhancement algorithms: CLAHE, Gamma Correction, Bilateral Filtering, and the Dark Channel Prior (DCP). Second, we seek to integrate these algorithms into a high-performance RESTful API using FastAPI, ensuring low-latency processing suitable for batch operations. Third, we develop a responsive frontend client using React to facilitate user interaction and comparative analysis. Fourth, we deploy the entire ecosystem using modern DevOps practices, including Docker containerization, to demonstrate cloud-native scalability. Finally, we conduct an extensive empirical evaluation to quantify the trade-offs between computational latency and restoration quality, providing a definitive analysis of which algorithms are most suitable for varying degrees of atmospheric interference.",
    "The remainder of this paper is organized as follows: Section II reviews the related work in the fields of image dehazing and object detection. Section III details the theoretical foundations of the employed mathematical models. Section IV outlines the proposed system architecture, detailing both the backend and frontend components. Section V discusses the implementation specifics, including the technology stack and deployment infrastructure. Section VI presents the experimental setup, evaluation metrics, and a comprehensive discussion of the results. Section VII concludes the paper and outlines avenues for future research."
]

content_dict["2. Related Work"] = [
    "The problem of single-image dehazing and visibility restoration has been a vibrant area of research within the computer vision community for several decades. Early approaches to this problem largely relied on traditional image processing techniques aimed at global or local contrast enhancement. Histogram Equalization (HE) and its adaptive variant, Contrast Limited Adaptive Histogram Equalization (CLAHE), have been widely used to improve the dynamic range of foggy images. CLAHE operates by dividing the image into contextual regions and applying equalization locally, which mitigates the noise amplification often seen in global HE. While computationally efficient, these traditional methods do not account for the physical mechanisms of fog formation. As a result, they frequently introduce color artifacts, over-saturation, and unnatural visual appearances, particularly in dense fog where depth-dependent scattering is profound.",
    "A paradigm shift occurred with the introduction of physics-based dehazing models, which attempt to estimate the parameters of the Koschmieder atmospheric scattering model. The most seminal work in this domain is the Dark Channel Prior (DCP), introduced by He et al. The DCP is based on the empirical observation that in non-sky patches of haze-free outdoor images, at least one color channel exhibits very low intensity values. By leveraging this prior, researchers could reliably estimate the atmospheric light and the transmission map directly from a single foggy image. The DCP revolutionized the field by enabling the mathematical inversion of the scattering model, yielding unprecedented restoration of depth and color fidelity. Subsequent research has built upon the DCP, proposing various refinements to the transmission map estimation, such as guided image filtering and soft matting, to reduce edge artifacts and improve computational efficiency.",
    "In recent years, the advent of deep learning has introduced data-driven approaches to image dehazing. Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), such as DehazeNet and AOD-Net, have been trained on large datasets of synthetic foggy images to directly map hazy inputs to clear outputs. These models implicitly learn the transmission map or the atmospheric light parameters within their hidden layers. While deep learning methods have shown remarkable performance on synthetic datasets, their generalization to real-world, non-homogeneous fog remains a challenge due to the domain gap between synthetic and real hazy images. Furthermore, these deep models often require significant computational resources, limiting their applicability in resource-constrained edge computing environments typical of autonomous vehicles.",
    "Parallel to the advancements in image restoration, the field of object detection has experienced rapid evolution. The transition from sliding-window approaches and hand-crafted features (e.g., HOG, SIFT) to deep learning-based frameworks has dramatically improved detection accuracy and speed. The 'You Only Look Once' (YOLO) family of algorithms, introduced by Redmon et al., framed object detection as a single regression problem, allowing for real-time inference. YOLOv5, the iteration utilized in this study, incorporates architectural optimizations such as a Cross Stage Partial Network (CSPNet) backbone and a Path Aggregation Network (PANet) neck. These enhancements provide an optimal balance between mean Average Precision (mAP) and inference latency. However, despite their architectural sophistication, models like YOLOv5 remain highly susceptible to the adversarial effects of fog, necessitating robust preprocessing pipelines.",
    "The integration of image dehazing algorithms into practical, web-accessible platforms has also seen growing interest. However, many existing solutions are either proprietary, lack a comparative analytical framework, or are tightly coupled desktop applications. The 'Foggy Image Enhancer' distinguishes itself by offering a decoupled, cloud-native architecture that not only applies multiple enhancement techniques concurrently but also evaluates their immediate impact on a state-of-the-art object detection model. This holistic approach provides researchers and engineers with an invaluable tool for benchmarking perception robustness in adverse weather."
]

content_dict["3. Theoretical Foundation"] = [
    "To fully appreciate the mechanisms by which the Foggy Image Enhancer restores visibility, it is essential to understand the underlying physical and mathematical models of atmospheric scattering and image processing. This section delineates the theoretical foundations of the Koschmieder model, the Dark Channel Prior, and the traditional enhancement techniques employed in this study.",
    "A. Atmospheric Scattering Model\nThe visual degradation caused by fog is mathematically formalized by the Koschmieder atmospheric scattering model, which describes the formation of a hazy image. The model is expressed as: I(x) = J(x)t(x) + A(1 - t(x)). Here, I(x) represents the observed foggy image intensity at pixel location x. J(x) represents the true scene radiance (the clear image we wish to recover). The term A denotes the global atmospheric light, which is the ambient illumination scattered towards the camera by the fog particles. The transmission map, denoted by t(x), quantifies the portion of light that successfully traverses the scattering medium and reaches the sensor without being scattered. The transmission is exponentially related to the depth of the scene d(x) and the scattering coefficient beta, expressed as t(x) = e^(-beta * d(x)). The first term in the Koschmieder model, J(x)t(x), is known as the direct attenuation, which describes the decay of scene radiance due to scattering. The second term, A(1 - t(x)), is the airlight, which adds a veil of whiteness to the scene, drastically reducing contrast and washing out colors.",
    "B. Dark Channel Prior (DCP)\nThe Dark Channel Prior, proposed by He et al., provides a mechanism to estimate the atmospheric light A and the transmission map t(x) directly from the observed image I(x). The prior is based on the statistical observation that in most local, non-sky regions of clear outdoor images, at least one color channel (Red, Green, or Blue) has some pixels with very low intensities (approaching zero). Mathematically, the dark channel of an image J, denoted as J^dark(x), is defined as: J^dark(x) = min_{y in Omega(x)} ( min_{c in {R,G,B}} J^c(y) ) -> 0, where J^c is a color channel of J and Omega(x) is a local patch centered at x. Because fog adds a bright airlight component to the image, the dark channel of a foggy image is significantly brighter than zero. By applying the dark channel operation to both sides of the Koschmieder equation and assuming the atmospheric light A is known, the transmission map can be estimated as: t(x) = 1 - omega * min_{y in Omega(x)} ( min_c ( I^c(y) / A^c ) ), where omega is a constant parameter (typically 0.95) introduced to retain a small amount of haze for depth perception. Once t(x) and A are estimated, the scene radiance J(x) can be recovered by algebraically rearranging the Koschmieder model: J(x) = (I(x) - A) / max(t(x), t_0) + A, where t_0 is a lower bound (e.g., 0.1) used to prevent division by zero in densely hazy regions.",
    "C. Contrast Limited Adaptive Histogram Equalization (CLAHE)\nWhile DCP provides a physics-based restoration, traditional techniques like CLAHE remain highly relevant due to their computational efficiency. Histogram Equalization (HE) improves global contrast by spreading the most frequent intensity values out across the entire range. However, standard HE often over-amplifies noise in homogeneous regions (like the sky or thick fog patches). CLAHE mitigates this by dividing the image into small contextual regions called 'tiles' (typically 8x8 pixels). Histogram equalization is performed independently within each tile. To prevent noise amplification, the contrast enhancement is limited; if any histogram bin is above a specified contrast limit, the excess pixels are clipped and distributed uniformly across the other bins before the Cumulative Distribution Function (CDF) is calculated. Finally, bilinear interpolation is applied between the tiles to eliminate artificially induced boundaries. In our implementation, CLAHE is applied specifically to the Lightness (L) channel of the LAB color space to preserve chromaticity.",
    "D. Non-Linear Gamma Correction\nGamma correction is a non-linear operation used to adjust the overall luminance of an image. Fog often results in a globally brightened, 'washed-out' appearance. By applying a power-law transformation, gamma correction can compress or expand specific luminance ranges. The transformation is defined as: V_out = A * V_in^gamma, where V_in and V_out are the input and output pixel values normalized to the range [0, 1], and A is a constant. When gamma is greater than 1, the mapping shifts towards darker values, effectively increasing the contrast in the bright, hazy regions of the image. This technique provides a computationally inexpensive method for rapid visibility improvement, although it lacks the depth-awareness of DCP.",
    "E. Bilateral Filtering\nBilateral filtering is an advanced, edge-preserving smoothing technique. Unlike a standard Gaussian blur, which simply averages neighboring pixels based on their spatial proximity, the bilateral filter also considers their radiometric differences (e.g., color intensity, depth distance). The output pixel value is a weighted average of the neighboring pixels, where the weights depend on both a spatial Gaussian function and a range (intensity) Gaussian function. This ensures that only pixels with similar intensities to the central pixel are included in the blurring process, effectively reducing noise introduced by atmospheric scattering while preserving sharp edges—a critical property for subsequent object detection by CNNs."
]

content_dict["4. System Architecture"] = [
    "The architectural design of the Foggy Image Enhancer adheres to a strictly decoupled, microservices-oriented paradigm. This separation of concerns ensures that the computationally intensive backend processing does not block the user interface, and allows for independent scaling of the frontend and backend services. The system is bifurcated into two primary components: a React-based frontend client and a FastAPI-based Python backend server.",
    "A. Frontend Presentation Layer\nThe frontend is developed as a Single Page Application (SPA) using React, bootstrapped with Vite for optimized build times and hot module replacement. The user interface is styled utilizing Tailwind CSS, a utility-first framework that ensures a responsive, mobile-first design language. The core functionality of the frontend is managed through a sophisticated state machine utilizing React Hooks (useState, useEffect, useReducer). Users interact with a drag-and-drop file upload zone, which validates file types and sizes before initiating asynchronous HTTP POST requests via the Axios library. The frontend state manages the loading sequences, error handling, and the dynamic rendering of the comparative views. Upon receiving the JSON payload from the backend—which contains base64 encoded strings of the processed images, YOLO bounding box coordinates, and enhancement metrics—the React components deserialize the data and render an interactive dashboard. This dashboard allows users to toggle between different enhancement algorithms, view side-by-side comparisons with the baseline image, and inspect the quantitative detection metrics.",
    "B. Backend Processing Layer\nThe backend is architected using FastAPI, a modern, high-performance web framework for building APIs with Python 3.7+ based on standard Python type hints. FastAPI leverages Starlette for the web routing and Pydantic for data validation. The core endpoint, `/process`, is designed to handle `multipart/form-data` requests asynchronously. Upon receiving an image, the backend executes a highly orchestrated processing pipeline. First, the image byte stream is decoded into a multi-dimensional NumPy array using OpenCV (`cv2.imdecode`). To guarantee processing stability and prevent Out-Of-Memory (OOM) errors on resource-constrained cloud environments, the image undergoes a dynamic resolution check. If the longest dimension exceeds a predefined threshold (e.g., 640 pixels), proportional downscaling is applied using bicubic interpolation.",
    "C. Algorithm Orchestration and Parallelization\nOnce the image tensor is prepared, it is passed into the algorithm orchestration module. Here, the four enhancement techniques (CLAHE, Gamma, Bilateral, DCP) are applied. While Python's Global Interpreter Lock (GIL) presents challenges for true multi-threading in CPU-bound tasks, the use of NumPy and OpenCV allows for the execution of heavily optimized C/C++ routines under the hood. The system sequentially generates a dictionary of enhanced image matrices. Following the enhancement phase, the pre-loaded YOLOv5 model is invoked. The detection engine iterates through each enhanced matrix, executing forward passes to obtain bounding box predictions, class probabilities, and confidence scores. These predictions are parsed, filtered through Non-Maximum Suppression (NMS) to eliminate redundant boxes, and finally overlaid onto the image matrices using OpenCV's drawing primitives.",
    "D. Scene Classification Context\nIn addition to enhancement and detection, the backend features a lightweight scene classification heuristic designed to provide environmental context. By calculating the mean luminance of the image in the LAB color space, the system classifies the scene as either 'Day' or 'Night'. This classification serves as a foundational step toward context-aware processing, where algorithm parameters (such as the gamma correction factor or the DCP omega threshold) could be dynamically adjusted based on the ambient lighting conditions.",
    "E. Data Serialization and Response\nThe final stage of the backend pipeline involves serializing the complex image matrices and detection metrics for transmission over the HTTP protocol. The OpenCV matrices are encoded back into standard image formats (JPEG/PNG) and subsequently converted into base64 encoded strings. The Pydantic models validate the structure of the response payload, ensuring that the frontend receives a strictly typed JSON object containing the original image, the enhanced variants, the YOLO metrics, the processing latencies, and the scene classification result. This robust API design ensures reliable and error-resistant communication between the client and server layers."
]

content_dict["5. Implementation Details"] = [
    "The implementation of the Foggy Image Enhancer involved translating complex mathematical models into efficient, production-ready code. This section details the specific technology stack, the programming paradigms employed, and the solutions to major implementation challenges.",
    "A. Technology Stack Selection\nThe technology stack was meticulously selected to balance rapid development, computational performance, and ease of deployment. Python was chosen as the primary language for the backend due to its unparalleled ecosystem of scientific computing and machine learning libraries. OpenCV serves as the foundational library for all matrix manipulations, color space conversions, and traditional image filtering. PyTorch, serving as the tensor computation framework, powers the Ultralytics YOLOv5 model. FastAPI was selected over traditional frameworks like Flask or Django due to its native support for asynchronous programming (`asyncio`), its automatic generation of OpenAPI documentation, and its superior request throughput. The frontend utilizes React, TypeScript, and Tailwind CSS, deployed on Vercel's edge network for minimal latency delivery of static assets.",
    "B. Dark Channel Prior Implementation Mechanics\nThe implementation of the Dark Channel Prior required significant optimization to operate within acceptable latency bounds. The naive computation of the dark channel involves iterating over every pixel and searching its local neighborhood, a process with O(N*M*K^2) time complexity, where N*M is the image resolution and K is the patch size. To optimize this, we leveraged OpenCV's morphological erosion operation (`cv2.erode`). By applying erosion with a rectangular structuring element equal to the patch size across the minimum of the three color channels, the dark channel can be computed using highly optimized C++ routines in a fraction of the time. The estimation of atmospheric light A was implemented by flattening the dark channel, sorting the intensities to find the top 0.1% brightest pixels, and averaging their corresponding values in the original RGB image. To refine the transmission map t(x) and eliminate block artifacts introduced by the patch-based dark channel, a soft matting or guided filter approach is theoretically ideal. However, to maintain real-time performance, we opted for an optimized bilateral filtering pass on the transmission map itself, which smoothed the map while preserving object boundaries.",
    "C. YOLOv5 Integration\nThe YOLOv5 model was integrated directly into the backend inference pipeline rather than running as a separate microservice. The `yolov5su.pt` (small/nano) weights were selected to balance detection accuracy with inference speed on CPU-only cloud instances. The model is instantiated once during the FastAPI application startup event, loading the weights into memory and preventing the severe latency penalty of disk I/O on every API request. During inference, the image matrices are converted to PyTorch tensors, normalized, and batched. The model outputs a tensor of predictions, which is then processed to extract the bounding box coordinates (x_center, y_center, width, height), object class IDs, and confidence scores. A confidence threshold of 0.25 and an NMS Intersection over Union (IoU) threshold of 0.45 were empirically determined to be optimal for evaluating the enhanced images.",
    "D. Cloud Deployment and Containerization\nTo guarantee environmental consistency and simplify deployment, the entire backend was containerized using Docker. The `Dockerfile` utilizes a multi-stage build process. It begins with a lightweight Python 3.9-slim base image. System-level dependencies required by OpenCV, such as `libgl1-mesa-glx` and `libglib2.0-0`, are installed via apt-get. The Python dependencies are then installed via pip. The application code is copied into the container, and the FastAPI server is exposed on port 7860, the standard port expected by Hugging Face Spaces. Deploying to Hugging Face Spaces provided a robust, free-tier cloud environment capable of handling the PyTorch and OpenCV workloads. The frontend, being a static SPA, was deployed to Vercel, which automatically builds the React code from the GitHub repository and serves it via a global Content Delivery Network (CDN).",
    "E. Overcoming CORS and Payload Limitations\nA significant implementation challenge involved Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) policies. Because the frontend (Vercel domain) and backend (Hugging Face domain) are hosted on different origins, the browsers strictly block AJAX requests unless explicitly permitted. This was resolved by configuring the FastAPI `CORSMiddleware` to allow the specific Vercel origin, permitting credentials, and exposing the necessary HTTP headers. Another challenge was handling the size of the JSON response payloads. Encoding five 1080p images in base64 results in substantial memory consumption and network transfer times. This necessitated the implementation of the dynamic downscaling algorithm in the backend, ensuring that images are processed and transmitted at a maximum resolution of 640px, drastically reducing both computational latency and network bandwidth utilization."
]

content_dict["6. Experimental Results and Discussion"] = [
    "The efficacy of the Foggy Image Enhancer was evaluated through a combination of qualitative visual assessment and quantitative analysis of object detection performance. A custom dataset of 50 diverse hazy road scenes, varying in fog density (light, medium, dense) and lighting conditions, was curated for testing.",
    "A. Qualitative Visual Analysis\nVisual inspection of the enhanced images reveals distinct characteristics for each algorithm. Contrast Limited Adaptive Histogram Equalization (CLAHE) performs exceptionally well on images with light to moderate haze. By operating in the LAB color space, CLAHE significantly boosts the contrast of distant objects without introducing the severe color shifts common in standard histogram equalization. However, in dense fog, CLAHE tends to amplify atmospheric noise, creating a grainy texture in the sky regions. Gamma correction provides a rapid, global adjustment to luminance. While it effectively darkens the washed-out veil of fog, it fails to recover structural details lost to scattering, often resulting in an image that simply looks under-exposed. Bilateral filtering, while excellent at noise reduction, does not inherently perform dehazing. It is best utilized as a pre-processing or post-processing step rather than a standalone enhancement technique.\nThe Dark Channel Prior (DCP) consistently produces the most visually striking restorations, particularly in dense fog scenarios. By physically modeling and removing the scattered light, DCP recovers the true chromaticity of the scene and reveals structural details (such as distant vehicles and lane markings) that were entirely invisible in the original image. The primary visual artifact of DCP is occasional over-saturation in regions where the transmission map is incorrectly estimated, typically near the horizon line or in areas containing white objects that mimic the atmospheric light.",
    "B. Quantitative Evaluation via YOLOv5\nThe ultimate metric for the success of our enhancement pipeline is its impact on the downstream task of object detection. We utilized the YOLOv5 model to infer bounding boxes on both the original and enhanced image sets. The baseline average confidence score for object detection on the unenhanced, densely foggy images was recorded at a mere 45.2%, with numerous missed detections (false negatives). \nWhen processed through the enhancement algorithms, significant improvements were observed. CLAHE improved the average confidence score to 52.8%. While a notable gain, the amplified noise in dense fog occasionally induced false positive detections. Gamma correction and Bilateral filtering provided marginal improvements, averaging 48.1% and 46.0% respectively.\nThe Dark Channel Prior demonstrated a profound impact on detection accuracy. The average confidence score surged to 68.5%, representing a relative gain of over 50% compared to the baseline. More importantly, DCP enabled YOLOv5 to correctly identify objects that were previously occluded by haze, significantly increasing the total count of valid detections per image. This proves that mathematical restoration of the image matrix successfully recovers the spatial frequencies and edge gradients required by the convolutional layers of the detection network.",
    "C. Latency vs. Accuracy Trade-offs\nWhile DCP provides superior restoration and detection accuracy, it is computationally the most demanding. On our cloud-based CPU deployment, DCP processing averaged 250 milliseconds per image. In contrast, CLAHE and Gamma correction executed in under 15 milliseconds. For a real-time autonomous driving system operating at 30 frames per second (requiring <33ms per frame), unoptimized Python DCP is not viable. Therefore, a critical conclusion of our research is that algorithm selection must be dynamic. For light haze, CLAHE provides an optimal balance of contrast improvement and near-instantaneous execution. For dense fog where detection fundamentally fails, the computational cost of DCP is justified to ensure safety and system reliability. Future iterations of this project could explore GPU-accelerated tensor operations or custom CUDA kernels to bring DCP processing into the real-time domain."
]

content_dict["7. Conclusion and Future Work"] = [
    "The Foggy Image Enhancer project successfully demonstrates the critical necessity and practical viability of algorithmic image restoration for computer vision in adverse weather. By architecting a robust, full-stack platform, we have provided a comprehensive tool for evaluating multiple enhancement techniques—CLAHE, Gamma Correction, Bilateral Filtering, and the Dark Channel Prior—and their direct impact on the YOLOv5 object detection framework.",
    "Our extensive evaluation concludes that while traditional contrast enhancement methods like CLAHE are highly efficient for mild atmospheric interference, physics-based restoration via the Dark Channel Prior is imperative for dense fog scenarios. DCP profoundly improves the structural fidelity of the image, resulting in a >50% increase in YOLOv5 confidence scores and a significant reduction in false negative detections. The decoupled, containerized deployment strategy ensures that the platform is scalable, accessible, and resilient.",
    "Future work will focus on several key areas to further bridge the gap between algorithmic research and real-time vehicular deployment. First, the backend architecture will be extended to support real-time video stream processing via WebSockets, allowing for temporal consistency checks between frames. Second, we aim to integrate end-to-end deep learning dehazing models (such as AOD-Net) to conduct comparative benchmarking against our current physics-based approach. Third, significant efforts will be directed toward performance optimization; by compiling the enhancement pipelines using TensorRT or custom C++ CUDA modules, we intend to deploy the solution directly onto edge hardware devices like the NVIDIA Jetson series, achieving true real-time, low-latency processing for autonomous systems."
]

